In addition to national wealth and parasite stress, there are several broad concepts related to climate that have been advanced to understand aggression and violence in society (see 
 Figure 3). Examples include but are not limited to income inequality, trust, democracy, rule of law, market competitiveness, tight and loose cultures, and norms of civic cooperation (e.g., 
 Balliet & van Lange, 2013; 
 GÃ¤chter & Herrmann, 2009; 
 Gelfand et al., 2011; 
 Henrich et al., 2010; 
 van Lange, 2015; 
 Yamagishi, 2017). In addition to wealth, income equality may be important. For example, there is strong evidence that income inequality is a powerful determinant of aggression and violence across nations (see 
 Kenrick & Gomez Jacinto, 2013; 
 Wilkinson & Pickett, 2009). Income inequality also tends to be greater near the equator (
 van de Vliert & van Lange, 2017).
